Carousel Patterns
Use this reference when transforming dense content, generating multiple angles, or tightening a draft carousel.
Default Slide Density
Default length: 7 to 10 slides.
Headline: aim for 4 to 12 words.
Body copy: aim for 15 to 45 words per slide.
Slide focus: one idea, one job, one takeaway.
Visual cue: one simple cue per slide, such as comparison, checklist, timeline, quote pullout, diagram, stack, before-after, or annotated example.
If a slide needs more than two short body lines, split it or turn it into a sequence.
Carousel Arcs
How-To Framework
Use for tutorials, explainers, and educational source content.
Hook: promised outcome or avoided pain.
Why it matters.
Step 1 or principle 1.
Step 2 or principle 2.
Step 3 or principle 3.
Example or common mistake.
Recap checklist.
CTA.
Mistakes And Fixes
Use when the source identifies errors, misconceptions, or weak practices.
Hook: "Most people get X wrong."
Stakes: what the mistake costs.
Mistake 1 and fix.
Mistake 2 and fix.
Mistake 3 and fix.
Better workflow.
Save-worthy summary.
CTA.
Myth Versus Truth
Use for misconception-busting or contrarian content.
Hook: common belief versus better truth.
Why the myth persists.
Myth 1 / truth 1.
Myth 2 / truth 2.
Myth 3 / truth 3.
What to do instead.
Key takeaway.
CTA.
Before-After Transformation
Use for process improvements, rewrites, case studies, and operational lessons.
Hook: before-to-after result.
The old way.
Why it failed.
The shift.
New step or habit 1.
New step or habit 2.
The after state.
CTA.
Teardown
Use for reviewing an example, landing page, strategy, post, email, or process.
Hook: what is being dissected and why.
Context: who it is for.
Strong point.
Weak point.
Missed opportunity.
Better version or fix.
Repeatable lesson.
CTA.
Hook Patterns
Use a specific noun, audience, result, or tension.
"If you have [problem], stop starting with [weak move]."
"[Audience] keep missing this part of [task]."
"I would not turn [source/topic] into a carousel by summarizing it."
"The fastest way to make [topic] clearer: split it into [framework]."
"Before you post [content], find the one idea people will save."
"[Common advice] is not wrong. It is just incomplete."
Avoid:
"Unlock the secrets of..."
"In today's fast-paced world..."
"This will change everything..."
"You won't believe..."
Slide Role Bank
Hook: create curiosity or promise value.
Stakes: show why the reader should care.
Reframe: replace the old mental model.
Step: give one action.
Contrast: show old versus new, myth versus truth, or weak versus strong.
Example: make the abstract concrete.
Proof: cite a source-backed reason, result, or observed pattern.
Checklist: make the carousel save-worthy.
Recap: compress the takeaway.
CTA: invite a comment, save, share, download, reply, booking, or next step.
QA Checklist
Does slide 1 promise a specific payoff?
Can the carousel be understood without the original source?
Does each slide have a distinct role?
Is every claim traceable to the provided source or clearly labeled as an inference?
Are jargon and acronyms explained for the target audience?
Are visual cues tool-neutral and easy to execute?
Is the final CTA aligned with the user's goal?
Would removing any middle slide make the argument weaker? If not, cut or merge it.
